{{Use British English|date=February 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox cricketer | name = John Edrich | honorific_suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE}} | image = Cricket_no_pic.png | country = England | fullname = John Hugh Edrich | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1937|6|21|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Blofield]], [[Norfolk]], [[England]] | batting = Left-handed batsman | bowling = Right arm medium | international = true | testdebutdate = 6 June | testdebutyear = 1963 | testdebutagainst = West Indies | testcap = 415 | lasttestdate = 8 July | lasttestyear = 1976 | lasttestagainst = West Indies | odidebutdate = 5 January | odidebutyear = 1971 | odidebutagainst = Australia | odicap = 4 | lastodidate = 9 March | lastodiyear = 1975 | lastodiagainst = New Zealand | deliveries = overs | club1 = [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] | year1 = 1958–1978 | columns = 4 | column1 = [[Test cricket|Tests]] | matches1 = 77 | runs1 = 5,138 | bat avg1 = 43.54 | 100s/50s1 = 12/24 | top score1 = 310* | deliveries1 = 5 | wickets1 = – | bowl avg1 = n/a | fivefor1 = – | tenfor1 = – | best bowling1 = n/a | catches/stumpings1 = 43/– | column2 = [[One Day International|ODIs]] | matches2 = 7 | runs2 = 223 | bat avg2 = 37.16 | 100s/50s2 = –/2 | top score2 = 90 | deliveries2 = – | wickets2 = – | bowl avg2 = n/a | fivefor2 = – | tenfor2 = n/a | best bowling2 = n/a | catches/stumpings2 = –/– | column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]] | matches3 = 564 | runs3 = 39,790 | bat avg3 = 45.47 | 100s/50s3 = 103/188 | top score3 = 310* | deliveries3 = 91 | wickets3 = 0 | bowl avg3 = – | fivefor3 = 0 | tenfor3 = 0 | best bowling3 = – | catches/stumpings3 = 310/- | column4 = [[List-A|LA]] | matches4 = 160 | runs4 = 4,792 | bat avg4 = 35.23 | 100s/50s4 = 1/39 | top score4 = 108* | deliveries4 = – | wickets4 = – | bowl avg4 = n/a | fivefor4 = – | tenfor4 = n/a | best bowling4 = n/a | catches/stumpings4 = | date = 10 December | year = 2013 | source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/12490.html CricInfo }}
'''John Hugh Edrich''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}} (born 21 June 1937) is a former English [[first-class cricket]]er who, during a career that ran from 1956 to 1978, was considered one of the best batsmen of his generation.<ref name="Cap">{{cite book |title=If The Cap Fits |last=Bateman |first=Colin |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1993 |publisher=Tony Williams Publications |location= |isbn=1-869833-21-X |pages=60–61 |url= }}</ref> Born in [[Blofield]], [[Norfolk]], Edrich came from a cricketing family, his four cousins, [[Eric Edrich]], [[Bill Edrich]], [[Geoff Edrich]] and [[Brian Edrich]], all having played first-class cricket.<ref name="Cap"/> He was educated at the private Bracondale School between the ages of eight and seventeen, during which time he played cricket at weekends and was coached by former cricketer [[Cecil Boswell|C. S. R. Boswell]].
Edrich played for [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] and [[England cricket team|England]]. He was renowned for playing the cut, the cover drive and scoring off his legs, earning over the years a reputation for dogged fearlessness. His statistical achievements show that he was amongst the best players of his generation, playing a total of seventy-seven [[Test cricket|Test matches]] for England between 1963 and 1976, and scoring a triple-century in 1965 that is the fifth highest Test score for England.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_innings.html?class=1;id=1;type=team | title=Records / England / Test matches / High scores | publisher=ESPN CricInfo | accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>
A player during the time when [[One Day International]] cricket was in its infancy, he played, and top scored, in the first ever ODI match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284257.html | title=Records / One-Day Internationals / Batting records / Most runs in an innings (progressive record holder) | publisher=ESPN CricInfo | accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref> The cricket writer Colin Bateman described him as "unflinching, unselfish, and often unsmiling while going about his business in the middle, he was a fiercely formidable opener who knew his limitations and worked wonderfully within them".<ref name="Cap"/>
==Life and career== Having played four first-class matches for [[Combined Services]] in 1956 and 1957, whilst doing his [[National Service#National service in the United Kingdom|national service]], Edrich made his first-class debut for [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] in their final fixture of the 1958 season. The following year, he came to the fore, scoring 1,799 runs at an average of 52.91. Over the next four years he and [[Micky Stewart]] became a very effective opening partnership for the county, to the extent that both were called up for England for the Test series against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], who were dominating the sport at this time. Despite Edrich's strong performances for his county, he managed a total of only 108 Test runs in six innings facing bowlers including [[Wes Hall|Hall]], [[Garfield Sobers|Sobers]] and [[Charlie Griffith|Griffith]].
However, an opportunity to break back into the international side arose when [[Geoffrey Boycott]] was injured during [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]]'s tour of England in 1964. Edrich was called up to the side for the Second Test, at [[Lord's]], and did not disappoint, scoring 120. The match ended in a draw due to rain.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154875.html Cricketer of the Year], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved on 10 August 2007.</ref> However, he was not selected for the 1964–65 tour of South Africa.
Injuries to other players resulted in another recall to the England side for the Third Test against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]] in July 1965, where he scored 310 not out.<ref name="Cap"/> This innings spanned over eight hours, and included 52 fours and five sixes – 238 runs or 77% of his innings.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/128733.html Edrich's epoch] [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved on 8 August 2007</ref> Commentators{{Who|date=April 2011}} at the time said that he might have broken the existing Test record of 365 within another 90 minutes or so if his captain, [[M. J. K. Smith|Mike Smith]], had not felt it necessary to declare the innings closed.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}} However, a week later during the First Test against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], he suffered a blow to the head from a short-pitched delivery by [[Peter Pollock]]. This was before helmets came into use, and he was forced to retire hurt on 7 not out.<ref>[http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/12490.html John Edrich's Cricket profile] [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved on 29 July 2007</ref> [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]] named Edrich as [[Wisden Cricketer of the Year|Cricketer of the Year]] in 1966 for his achievements in 1965, alongside [[Colin Bland]], [[Dick Motz]], [[Graeme Pollock]] and brother [[Peter Pollock]]. As well as his Test triple century, he had scored a total of 2,319 runs at an average of 62.67 during the season, including eight hundreds. At one stage, in nine successive innings he scored 139, 121*, 205*, 55, 96, 188, 92, 105 and 310*. Not previously known as a big hitter, he struck forty-nine sixes during the course of the season. [[Image:John Edrich Graph.png|left|thumb|350px|John Edrich's Test career performance graph]]
He had by now become an established member of the England batting line-up, rarely omitted unless injured. Beginning with the [[1965–66 Ashes series]], he sometimes batted at number three rather than, as hitherto, opening the innings. In the [[1970–71 Ashes series]] his 687 runs (52.85) kept him at the crease for 33 hours and 26 minutes, a record for a Test series until broken by [[Glenn Turner]] against West Indies the next season. His form at this time helped England play 27 consecutive Tests without defeat in 1968–71, and lose only one Test out of 40 in 1966–71.
Edrich played in the first-ever [[One Day International]] (ODI), on 5 January 1971 against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]]. After the Third Test had been called off due to rain, the umpires called for an unscheduled match, consisting of 40 eight-ball overs per side. Edrich top-scored with 82 runs, thus scoring the first half-century in an ODI, and won the first [[Man of the Match]] award in ODI history.
The following summer, Surrey won the [[County Championship]] for the first time since 1958, with Edrich's batting being an important factor in the county's success. By now, Stewart had dropped down the order to number three, and Edrich had formed another successful opening partnership with [[Mike Edwards (cricketer)|Mike Edwards]]. Stewart retired after the 1972 season, and from 1973 to 1977 Edrich succeeded him as Surrey's captain.
On the tour of Australia in 1974–75, his fortune regarding injuries did not improve. In the first [[Test cricket|Test]] a ball from aggressive pace bowler [[Dennis Lillee]] struck his hand and broke it, although he was able to continue batting. In the Fourth Test, the then [[Captain (cricket)|captain]] [[Mike Denness]] dropped himself and Edrich was subsequently named as captain.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/222039.html "The Captain Who Dropped Himself]" [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved on 30 July 2007</ref> He had little luck in that game when Lillee broke his ribs with the first ball of his second innings, although he did recover to bat later on, scoring 33 runs. England lost the test, and it was to be his only appearance as captain.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/ashes_tour/article634109.ece Egos battered, Bruised and Bewildered] ''The Times''. Retrieved 30 July 2007.</ref><ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,1931311,00.html Heads we lose] ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved on 30 July 2007.</ref>
During the 1977 county cricket season, Edrich scored his 100th first-class century, playing for Surrey against [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]]. In the same year he was appointed an MBE for services to cricket. Edrich finished his first-class career in 1978, having scored 39,790 runs. He became a Test selector in 1981.<ref>[http://stats.acscricket.com/famous_cricketers/86/index.html Famous cricketers] ACS Cricket. Retrieved on 24 April 2016.</ref>
In 1995 he was named as England's batting coach.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/868169.stm Edrich diagnosed with incurable leukemia], [[BBC News]]. Retrieved 7 August 2007.</ref> In the summer of 2000, it was announced that he had been diagnosed with a rare form of incurable [[leukaemia]] known as [[Waldenström macroglobulinemia|Waldenstrom's]], and he was told that he had seven years to live. In an interview with ''[[The Independent]]'', following his diagnosis, Edrich said:
{{quote|I hadn't seen a doctor for about 10 years, but I'd been feeling tired for a while. Having taken blood tests they discovered leukaemia. It was quite a shock. You can't fight it. You have to have faith in your consultant and the treatment. I asked how it was going to affect my lifestyle. They said I would feel tired from time to time and would have to live with it. I think we've got to be grateful for what we've had. I did something which I loved and had the ability to play cricket at the highest level.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/edrich-battles-with-incurable-leukemia-712180.html Edrich battles with incurable leukemia] ''[[The Independent]]''. Retrieved on 24 April 20016</ref>}}
In 2006–07 he served as President of [[Surrey County Cricket Club]]. In 2012 he said he had been cured of cancer by a course of injections of [[mistletoe]] extract, and was fit and active again. He now lives in [[Aberdeenshire]].<ref name="mistletoe">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-2208460/Howzat-Former-England-batsman-claims-mistletoe-injections-cured-cancer-killed-years-ago.html|title=Howzat? Former England batsman claims mistletoe injections cured cancer which should have killed him five years ago|last=Reynolds|first=Emma|date=25 September 2012|work=[[Mail Online]]|accessdate=26 November 2013}}, quoted in ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'' 2013, p. 1579.</ref>
==International awards== ===One Day Internationals=== ====Man of the Match awards==== {| class="wikitable" style="width:100%; margin-left:10px" |- ! style="background:#87cefa; color:black;" |# ! style="background:#87cefa; color:black;" |Opponent ! style="background:#87cefa; color:black;" |Venue ! style="background:#87cefa; color:black;" |Date ! style="background:#87cefa; color:black;" |Match Performance ! style="background:#87cefa; color:black;" |Result |- style="background:White;" | 1 | [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]] | [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]], [[Melbourne]] | 5 January 1971 | 82 (119 balls, 4×4) | {{cr|AUS}} won by 5 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.howstat.com/cricket/Statistics/Matches/MatchScorecard_ODI.asp?MatchCode=0048|title=1970–1971 Australia v England – 1st Match – Melbourne|work=HowStat|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> |- style="background:White;" | 2 | [[India national cricket team|India]] | [[Headingley Cricket Ground]], [[Leeds]] | 13 July 1974 | 90 (97 balls, 6×4, 1×6) | {{cr|ENG}} won by 4 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.howstat.com/cricket/Statistics/Matches/MatchScorecard_ODI.asp?MatchCode=0059|title=1974 England v India – 1st Match – Leeds|work=HowStat|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> |}
