'''Publius Metilius Nepos''' (c. 45&ndash;127) was a [[Roman Empire|Roman]] [[Roman senate|senator]] during the late 1st century. He is known to have been [[Roman consul|suffect consul]] in the ''[[nundinium]]'' of September-December 91,<ref>Paul Gallivan, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/638472 "The Fasti for A. D. 70-96"], ''[[Classical Quarterly]]'', 31 (1981), pp. 191, 218</ref> and was appointed [[Roman governor|Governor]] of [[Roman Britain|Britannia]] by the Emperor [[Domitian]] before his death, and held the post until 98.<ref>Anthony Birley, ''The Fasti of Roman Britain'' (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1981), p. 83</ref>

While governor, he may have founded the [[Colonia (Roman)|colonies]] of ''Colonia Domitiana Lindensium'' ([[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]]) and ''Colonia Nervia Glevensium'' ([[Gloucester]]).

Further details about Nepos are more difficult to be confident about. The inscriptions of the [[Frater Arvale]] record a '''Publius Metilius Sabinus Nepos''' as one of their brotherhood who attended their meetings in the years 105, 110, and 111, who had died by 26 February 118 when a successor was co-opted in his place.<ref name=Birley-84>Birley, ''Fasti'', p. 84</ref> On the other hand, a papyrus from [[Roman Egypt]] records the joint consulate of P. Metilius Nepos II and [[Marcus Annius Libo]] for 128; apparently Nepos died in late 127, and his term assigned to another person. Some assistance is provided by the presence of a "Metilius" -- who could be Publius Metilius Nepos or Publius Metilius Sabinus Nepos -- as suffect consul in 103. It is likely we have two consular senators with similar names: one died before February 118, the other in late 127.<ref name=Birley-84/>

[[Pliny the Younger]] addressed several letters to a Nepos, and at least one more to a Sabinus. It is not yet possible to determine which Nepos Pliny was writing to, nor even assure he was writing to either of these Metilii Nepotes.

The question of children and descendants is an open one. On one hand there is a [[Publius Metilius Secundus|Publius Metilius P.f. Secundus]], suffect consul in 123, who could be the son of either Metilii Nepotes; on the other, Anthony Birley notes there are two [[polyonymy|polyonymous]] senators of the next generation whose names are part of their nomenclature: [[Marcus Sedatus Severianus]] consul in 153, and [[Marcus Metilius Aquillius Regulus]] consul in 157.<ref>Birley, ''Fasti'', p. 85</ref> The solution awaits further information.

