'''Simon van den Bergh''' (October 26, 1819 in [[Geffen (Netherlands)|Geffen]] – April 6, 1907 in [[Rotterdam]]) was a Dutch businessperson. He founded a margarine factory in the Netherlands that became world-famous.<ref>{{cite news |title=MARGARINE KING DEAD.; Simon Vandenbergh Started in Business as a Small Shopkeeper |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9A02E1DA1331E733A25753C1A9629C946697D6CF |work=New York Times |date=1907-04-10 |page=4 }}</ref>
In 1888, the same year his son [[Samuel van den Bergh|Samuel]] joined the company, he opened a factory in [[Kleve]], the ''Van den Bergh Margarine Works''. By announcing it was for the industrial manufacture of margarine, he was able to circumvent the high tariffs of the German Reich on butter and margarine. The factory introduced the Sanella brand in 1904, made from almond milk.
In the summer of 1929 (after the death of Simon van den Bergh) the Jurgens & Prince Margarine Works in Goch and Van den Bergh in Kleve merged to become [[Margarine Unie]]. The newly merged company then combined with English soap manufacturer [[Lever Brothers]] to create the modern company [[Unilever]].
